		["mod_name"] = "Sliding wall cars with 4 axles (G1 profile)",
		["mod_desc"] = "In the early 1970s, the first prototypes of four-axle sliding-wall wagons were introduced, which stood out at the time due to their large loading areas for palletized cargo. Nowadays, these wagons have become indispensable. This package includes a significant portion of four-axle sliding-wall wagons with G1 profile (standard size) that have been in use over the past decades. Starting with the prototypes from 1973, various paint schemes in the mid-1980s, and up to the modern Habbis wagons of AAE, built in 1995.",
		["HB1_desc"] = "In 1976, Waggonfabrik Uerdingen (DUEWAG) developed a sliding wall wagon with four axles and three walls on each side, which allowed the wagon to be opened by one third from both sides. Initially, these wagons were supplied in limited numbers to Eisenbahnverkehrsmittel-AG (EVA), but later they went to the then newly founded company Cargowaggon. Cargowaggon was created in 1979 through a tender to manufacture and manage new rail cars for Ford Europe to facilitate the transport of vehicle parts between different European factories. However, the wagons were soon replaced by other models such as Habins 3, and the last examples were retired or sold by the 1990s. Today, isolated wagons can still be found in Romania (GFR).",
		["HB2_desc"] = "One of the first large, four-axle H cars with several sliding walls, built approx. 1973 by Waggon-Union Siegen). The only adjusters at that time were Railship and Transwaggon. At the end of the 1970s, DB needed additional ss-capable sliding wall cars since the establishment of its postal freight train network and thus leased HB2 from TWA. These postal express cars were redesignated as Habiqss and received their own paint scheme with a postal emblem starting in 1977. After the discontinuation of the rail mail service (and later also the liquidation of Railship), all wagons came (back) to TWA. Nowadays, however, these cars are rarely seen, but most models continue to run in Romania (bought up by GFR, among others).",
		["HB3_desc"] = "In 1984, WU Siegen built a series of several different sliding wall wagons for Eisenbahnverkehrsmittel-AG (EVA), including the Habins 3. All wagons were operated under the Frankfurt-based company Cargowaggon (founded in 1979), which specialized in the purchase of wagons for subleasing them to other customers (e.g. BMW).  In 1998, Cargowaggon was bought by GERS and its fleet was taken over. The Habins 3 changed hands several times since then (GERS - DB - GERS - TOUAX), but can still be found today.",		
		["HBAAE_desc"] = "Following a prototype, the Ahaus-Alstätter-Eisenbahn (AAE) procured over 1,000 Habbins sliding wall cars (AAE types H1 and H3) in 1995, which were built at Waggonbau Niesky in cooperation with Tatravagonka Poprad until 1999. These were leased to numerous customers throughout Europe. In 1996, DB AG also leased a total of 390 of these cars, but they were unrecognizable as DB vehicles because they continued to operate under the AAE regime (68 AAE). Although many of the former SJ and Nordwaggon AAE cars were also later purchased by ÖBB, the latter nevertheless additionally owned its own slightly modified variants of the Habbin as early as 1998. In 2015, AAE was bought out by VTG, and the cars now operate under AAEC.",
		["HB345_desc"] = "In 1987, DB procured 100 bogie sliding wall cars from WU Siegen. DB lined up 50 cars, each with eight interlocking partitions, as Habbikks-tt 346 - redesignated as Habbills 346 until 1993. In 1997, DB AG prepared a car as a test car for transporting paper rolls; at the same time, the Habbis 345 276 7 013 selected for this purpose received a traffic red paint scheme - the only car of this type to date.",
		["HB6_desc"] = "In the early 1980s, Transwaggon procured a series of modern sliding-wall cars with three sliding walls per side. Like their predecessors, these cars were used for transporting large-volume, light goods as well as cardboard boxes and packaging materials. Some companies, such as Opel and Viessmann, also included wagons of this type in their fleets in the mid-1980s, although Viessmann's variant (HB63) required slight modifications. These distinctive variants all disappeared in the early 2000s, and today the cars are owned exclusively by Transwaggon and ERR.",
		["HB901_desc"] = "After Swedish Transport Company Nordwaggon underwent a restructuring in 1990, the company made the decision to add four-axle covered bogie cars, known as Habins, to its fleet. Between 1992 and 1994, a total of 203 Habins 901 were delivered by Transtech, a Finnish company. When Transwaggon took over Nordwaggon, the cars were taken over, with only the addresses changed. They are still recognizable as former Nordwaggon wagons and are still in service today under TWA.",
		["sound_check"] = "Activate custom sound?",
